First-class functions.

Functions are values in python. You can assign them to variables. Store them in lists, dicts, sets. Pass them as arguments to other functions. Return them from other functions.

This is what makes higher-order operations work — map, filter, sorted with a key. It is what makes decorators possible in notebook seven. And it lets you build dispatch tables of functions keyed by a string.

In code, picture def apply taking f and x, returns f of x. Apply of string dot upper and hello returns capital hello. Apply of lambda n colon n times n, and seven, returns forty-nine. Function as return value — already shown with make-adder. Function in a data structure — handlers equals a dict mapping uppercase to str dot upper, lowercase to str dot lower, reverse to a lambda. Looking up and calling gives the corresponding transformation.
